<div style="background-color: white; color: black; border: 2px solid black; padding: 15px 20px; margin: 1em 8em; box-shadow: 1px 1px 10px black inset; overflow:hidden;">
[[File:Lamprey shrimp.webp|300x300px|right]]
<span style="font-size: 25px;">Lamprey Shrimp | Genus: Apostecarida</span>

'''Lamprey Shrimp''' are small parasitic crustaceans found in the brackish waters of '''The Perennial Marshes'''' inner lakes. Being heavily specialized for an ectoparasitic lifestyle, '''Lamprey Shrimp''' are a micropredatory group that preys on many larger lifeforms throughout a single lifetime. While waiting for a host to feed from, '''Lamprey Shrimp''' rest in the sediment, using small inset eyes to scout for potential hosts. A large set of leaping legs propels the '''Lamprey Shrimp''' from the waterbed, using its broad legs to accelerate itself towards a host before latching to the host's body with its jaws. '''Lamprey Shrimp''' are, however, exposed to attacks while attached; their shells are not completely covered on the sides, allowing small scavenging worms to enter the inner portion of its body and feed on the tender interior flesh.

The exoskeleton of '''Lamprey Shrimp''' is tougher and thicker in comparison to most crustaceans. The "tail" in most species is arched and tucked into the underside of the main body, forming a protective shell that prevents other animals from harming it while attached to a host. The main distinguishing feature is the oral leg structures, with the feeding appendages being more adapted for scraping flesh and feeding on the blood within a host. It is paired with the tip of the head to form a rudimentary "jaw" used to firmly clamp itself to the host's body.</div>

<div style="background-color: white; color: black; border: 2px solid black; padding: 15px 20px; margin: 1em 8em; box-shadow: 1px 1px 10px black inset; overflow:hidden;">
[[File:Justinventedanewbug.webp|300x300px|right]]
<span style="font-size: 25px;">Orvilids | Order: Sepliforamens</span>

'''Orvilids''' are a group of insects closest related to earwigs, exclusively present on the shores of freshwater areas. They lack wings and are more adapted for swimming — a broad, flat tail and modified wing-fins allow for efficient navigation within water. In contrast to most other insects, '''Orvilids''' are relatively large, with sizes comparable to that of katydids or stickbugs. '''Orvilids''' have an omnivorous diet and feed on root material, other insects, small fish, and small [[Kingdom Venatrexima|Venatrexens.]]

The most defining characteristic of '''Orvilids''' is their ability to produce an exceptionally sticky mucus from glands adjacent to their mandibles. Often using the substance to form clusters of soil for building burrows, they are mostly social (albeit in low numbers, averaging 15-25 in larger colonies) though without specified roles. '''Orvilid''' colonies are rather simplistic, with all members contributing roughly equally to resources, food, and young. The only major role difference is with the females' lesser contribution to hunting, as they instead watch over their young.</div>

<div style="background-color: white; color: black; border: 2px solid black; padding: 15px 20px; margin: 1em 8em; box-shadow: 1px 1px 10px black inset; overflow:hidden;">
[[File:Pseudogastridea.jpg|300x300px|right]]
<span style="font-size: 25px;">Pseudogastrids | Family: Pseudogastridoda</span>

'''Pseudogastrids''' comprise a family of aquatic [[Kingdom Venatrexima|Venatrexens]] characterized by their passive predation methods, relying on drawing prey into a stomach-like cavity hidden under the sediment. Many '''pseudogastrids''' reside in fresh or brackish waters, with only few known species preferring higher salinity levels. As a recently discovered family, little is known about this group's deeper anatomy or life cycle.</div>
